{{Unreferenced|date=March 2009}} [[File:Petr Kireevski.jpg|thumb|200px|Pyotr Kireevsky; portrait by [[Emmanuil Dmitriev-Mamonov]].]] '''Pyotr Vasilievich Kireevsky''' (23 February 1808 in [[Belyovsky District|Dolbino]], Kaluga Governorate &ndash; 6 November 1856) was a Russian [[folklorist]] many of whose materials remain unpublished to this day.
Kireevsky was an ardent [[Slavophile]] like his elder and more famous brother [[Ivan Kireevsky|Ivan Vasilievich]] (although [[Friedrich Wilhelm Joseph Schelling|Schelling]] thought Pyotr the more original of the two). He spent his entire life collecting folk songs and lyrics. Some of these were contributed by [[Alexander Pushkin]], [[Nikolai Gogol]], [[Aleksey Koltsov]], and [[Vladimir Dahl]].
During his lifetime, Kireevsky printed only the first volume of his collection, containing "spiritual lyrics". Ten other volumes were brought out posthumously, between 1860 and 1874, under the supervision of [[Pyotr Bessonov]]. Another anthology was published in 1911; it was used by [[Igor Stravinsky]] to arrange his libretto for the ballet ''[[Les Noces]]'' (first performed in 1923). ---- {{efron}}
