According to [[Dagobert D. Runes]], Dictionary of Philosophy, 1942, '''theistic personalism''' is "the theory most generally held by [[Personalists]] that God is the ground of all being, immanent in and transcendent over the whole world of reality. It is pan-psychic but avoids [[pantheism]] by asserting the complementary nature of immanence and transcendence which come together in and are in some degree essential to all personality. The term is used for the modern form of [[theism]]. Immanence and transcendence are the contrapletes of personality." <ref>[http://www.ditext.com/runes/t.html www.ditext.com] </ref>
